Investigation of housing prices in the Seattle area

Introduction

This project delves into predicting the cost of houses in the Seattle housing area. With a shared dataset, I embarked on exploring various models to forecast housing prices based on specific variables. In order to create these models, careful consideration was given to selecting the most relevant variables, and diagnostic plots were employed to assess the models appropriateness.

Drawing insights from articles like 5 factors that affect a homes value, I focused on investigating the impact of location, home size, age, and renovations on housing prices in the Seattle area. By examining the provided data, I aimed to uncover the true influence of these factors on housing prices.

To tackle this task, I leveraged Multiple Linear Regression, which enabled the creation of several models. Additionally, I used diagnostic plots to ensure the models validity. An intriguing aspect was observing how the complexity of the models affected the \(r^2\) value. Balancing complexity and predictive power, I made thoughtful decisions regarding the number of factors to include in each multiple linear regression model.

Through this personal project, I aimed to gain valuable insights into the housing market dynamics in Seattle and provide a reliable method for predicting housing costs in the area.

Data Investigation & Cleaning

library(tidyverse)
library(GGally)
options(scipen = 999)
housing <- read.csv(file.choose())

housing1 <- housing %>% 
  select(price, bedrooms, bathrooms, sqft_living15, floors, waterfront, view, condition, grade, yr_built, yr_renovated, lat, long)

house2 <- housing1 %>% 
  mutate(Waterfront = ifelse(waterfront == TRUE, 1, 0),
         recentlyRenovated = ifelse(yr_renovated > 2010, 1, 0),
         familyHome = ifelse(bedrooms > 3, 1, 0)) %>% 
  select(-waterfront, yr_renovated)

ggplot(data = house2, aes(x = sqft_living15, y = price)) +
  geom_point(color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Figure 1. Using square feet to predict price", y = "Price", x ="Square Feet" )

Figure 1

This model is a simple graph to see if Square Feet can be used to predict the price of the homes. It seems like there could be some trend but way there are too many outliers on this graph.

ggplot(data = house2, aes(x = sqft_living15, y = log10(price))) +
  geom_point(color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Figure 2. Using square feet to predict log 10 price", y = "Price", x ="Square Feet" )

Figure 2

This model takes the log10 of the price and plots the square feet. As you can see there seems to be a much better trend this way. May be worth investigating.

ggplot(data = house2, aes(x = sqft_living15, y = sqrt(price))) +
  geom_point(color = "red") +
  labs(title = "Figure 3. Using square feet to predict sqrt of price", y = "Price", x ="Square Feet" )

Figure 3

This model takes the square root of each price vs the square feet. It does not look as good as figure two but still better than figure one. This model is not better than figure two and probably more complicated to explain then the other two figures. To explain this model correctly we would have to square both sides and price would be explained by \(ft^4\). That is hard to explain so this model was not investigated any further.

Cleaning

I got rid of sqft_living just used sqft_living15 as it has the most recent sqft of the homes. It would not make sense to keep both as they are either repeating the same information or updating some of the homes that got renovated. The reason why house ID was not removed is because I will later be using it to predict the prices of the NA houses. The other square feet measurements were tossed as they are already represented under the sqft_living15 column. I did not get rid of the yr_renovated because as you will see, I added a column saying if the house was renovated or not. I also decided to get rid of the zipcode, as it would be silly to try and predict the price linearly with a given zipcode, but having the information as longitude and latitude will allow us to do it.

Feature Engineering

I created three new variables. The first one returns 1 if it has a waterview. The other variable shows if it was renovated after 2010, and the last variable is if the house has four or more bedrooms. I labeled these houses as family homes. I then got rid of waterfront and yr_renovated column since it is represented in two of the new variables I created.

Creating The Model

Preliminary Model

set.seed(150) 
training_rows <- sample(1:nrow(house2), size=floor(0.75*nrow(house2)))
Training <- house2[training_rows, ]
Testing <- house2[-training_rows, ]
#ggpairs(Training)

RMSE <- function(pred, obs){
  RMSE <- sqrt(mean((pred - obs)^2, na.rm = TRUE))
  return(RMSE)
}

library(olsrr)
modelAll<- lm(data = Training, price~.)
#summary(modelAll)

bestSubsetSelect <- ols_step_best_subset(modelAll)
#bestSubsetSelect
#choose the model based on how many variables you want


ggplot(data = bestSubsetSelect, aes(x = n, y = rsquare))+
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Figure 9. Best Subset Models", x= "Model Number", y = "R-Squared")

bestSubsetModel <- lm(data = Training, price ~ grade + lat + view + bathrooms + yr_built + sqft_living15 + Waterfront)
#summary(bestSubsetModel)

testingPredictions <- predict.lm(bestSubsetModel,  newdata = Testing)
trainingPredictions <- predict.lm(bestSubsetModel, newdata = Training)

trainingRMSE = RMSE(trainingPredictions, Training$price)
testingRMSE = RMSE(testingPredictions, Testing$price)

library(car)
#vif(bestSubsetModel)
#ggpairs(bestSubsetModel)

Figure 9 shows the \(r^2\) of the model depending on the complexity. So the more factors we use the lower the \(r^2\) gets. We can see that the \(r^2\) caps at about 7 factors. So the model I used for the best select method used 7 factors.

RMSE

The training RMSE for the best select model is 196970.8.

The testing RMSE for the best select model is 198970.3

R Squared

The \(r^2\) of this model is \(0.654\)

set.seed(150)
mixedSubsetSelect <-ols_step_both_p(modelAll)
#mixedSubsetSelect

mixedSubsetModel <- lm(data = Training, price ~ grade + lat + view + bathrooms + yr_built + sqft_living15 + Waterfront + condition)
#summary(mixedSubsetModel)

testingPredictions1 <- predict.lm(mixedSubsetModel,  newdata = Testing)
trainingPredictions1 <- predict.lm(mixedSubsetModel, newdata = Training)

trainingRMSE1 = RMSE(trainingPredictions1, Training$price)
testingRMSE1 = RMSE(testingPredictions1, Testing$price)

The Better Model

The second model is slightly better than the first so I will use this one.

\(price = 132300.0*grade + 532200.0*lat + 65110.0*view + 98400.0*bathrooms\) \(- 2757.0*yrBuilt + 75.37*sqft + 548400.0*waterfront + 22450.0*condition - 20820000.0\)

This equation means that given the grade, lat, sqft, condition number of views, bathrooms, whether it has a waterfront or not, it increases the price of the house, while the year built actually decrease the closer to the present the house was built. This is likely due to the fact that the older houses are in the more desirable locations of Seattle.

library(ggfortify)
autoplot(mixedSubsetModel, title =  "Figure 10.")

These are the diagnostic plots. Given these plots linear regression is logical. The standardized Residual vs leverage plot is not the best but unfortunately, some of the most expensive houses are much more expensive then what the linear model predicts. After doing ggpairs, I saw linear correlations with price and most of the variables in the model. This is done by plotting all factors vs the price and seeing if there is a positive linear correlation. Most of these factors showed appropriate conditions for multiple linear regression.

RMSE

The testing RMSE for the best select model is 199898

R Squared

Taking New Data

houseSubset <- read.csv(file.choose())

housing1 <- houseSubset %>% 
  select(price, bedrooms, bathrooms, sqft_living15, floors, waterfront, view, condition, grade, yr_built, yr_renovated, lat, long, houseID)

house2 <- housing1 %>% 
  mutate(waterfront = ifelse(waterfront == TRUE, 1, 0),
         recentlyRenovated = ifelse(yr_renovated > 2010, 1, 0),
         familyHome = ifelse(bedrooms > 3, 1, 0)) %>% 
  select(-yr_renovated)


set.seed(150) 
training_rows <- sample(1:nrow(house2), size=floor(0.75*nrow(house2)))
Training <- house2[training_rows, ]
Testing <- house2[-training_rows, ]

mixedSubsetModel1 <- lm(data = Training, price ~ grade + lat + view + bathrooms + yr_built + sqft_living15 + waterfront + condition)
#summary(mixedSubsetModel1)
#ggpairs(mixedSubsetModel1)

testingPredictions1 <- predict.lm(mixedSubsetModel1,  newdata = Testing)
trainingPredictions1 <- predict.lm(mixedSubsetModel1, newdata = Training)

trainingRMSESubset = RMSE(trainingPredictions1, Training$price)
testingRMSESubset = RMSE(testingPredictions1, Testing$price)

New Model

RMSE

After we created a new model with the same factors we get lower RMSE values and \(r^2\) values for the model. The training RMSE for the new model with the new data set is 339355.6. The testing RMSE for the new model with the new data set is 403511.7

R Squared

The \(r^2\) of this model is 0.720

Equation

\(price = 217700.0*bathrooms + 185.9*sqft + 76630.0*view +827300.0*waterfront\) \(+ 215100.0*grade - 5310.0*yearBuilt + 356600.0*lat - 119700.0*floors - 8231000.0\)

This model is very similar to the original model except for a few factors. The floors was added with a negative impact to the price, so more floors means that it decreases the price. This could be because typically houses with many floors lack overall area of the house which is used to increase the price. Condition was also not a good predictor for price in this model. It could be because this subset is likely all houses from similar communities. If the conditions are roughly the same given the houses then the data for condition is likely not a good predictor. We can see that waterfronts have a bigger impact on the price as well. This could be due to the fact that this is likely a more expensive subset of houses.

Conclusion

Given the data, I was able to find multiple linear regression models for both datasets to help predict the price of houses in the Seattle area. The second dataset needed to use different predictors in order to predict the price. I had to use floors and get rid of the conditions factor.The RMSE was high only because the prices of the houses were all fairly high and varied quite a bit given the factors. The RMSE was much better for the first dataset than the second. This could be due to the fact that better predictors needed to be created for the second dataset. Overall, the models built are appropriate and can be used to predict the prices houses in the Seattle area.
